# Carbon From Above

### Orbital Diamond Fabrication from Asteroid Carbon Feedstock

**Solbakken Research Initiative · March 2026 · Version 5**

> Speculative / Pre-Experimental — this is a framework paper, not a report of experimental results.

-----

## Overview

Silicon’s radiation vulnerability is a structural problem for orbital AI compute. This paper proposes a closed-loop orbital supply chain converting ureilite asteroid carbon into CVD-grown diamond substrates via concentrated solar power — co-located with compute infrastructure.

Diamond’s 5.5 eV bandgap raises single-event upset (SEU) thresholds far above silicon’s 1.1 eV. Its thermal conductivity (~2,000 W/mK vs silicon’s ~150 W/mK) enables heat spreading in vacuum without convection. Its UV–IR transparency suits photonic AI architectures directly.

The framework is speculative. The constituent technologies — microgravity CVD (Wake Shield, 1995), ISRU chemistry (MOXIE, 2021), deployable solar concentrators — exist. Integration is the challenge.

-----

## Three-Phase Roadmap

|Phase            |Focus                                      |Horizon  |
|-----------------|-------------------------------------------|---------|
|1 — Validate     |ISS pyrolysis; CubeSat CVD; cost models    |2026–2030|
|2 — Prototype    |50 kW furnace; cm² wafers; purification    |2030–2040|
|3 — Industrialize|Asteroid ISRU reactors; orbital lithography|2040–2050|

-----

## Key Claims

- Ureilite asteroids contain 2–4 wt% carbon, graphite-dominant, suitable as CVD feedstock
- 500 m² orbital solar concentrator at 1,366 W/m² meets CVD kilowatt-scale demand
- Estimated yield: ~2 kg diamond/year at zero fuel cost
- Radiation-hard silicon sacrifices 30–50% die area to redundancy; diamond addresses this at the material level

-----

## Kill Conditions

Two Phase 1 kill conditions gate the program:

- CH₄ contamination from ureilite pyrolysis that cannot be remediated by catalytic purification
- No viable terrestrial cost crossover identified by technoeconomic model

